How to Write an Eggdrop Module

Note: This guide covers simple single-file modules.

CREATING A MODULE

1. Create a src/mod/MODULE.mod directory in your Eggdrop source tree
   (where MODULE is your module name) and enter that directory.

2. Create a meson.build file in your module directory. Use the following
   as a template (replace 'mymodule' with your actual module name):

    eggdrop_mod_mymodule = shared_library('mymodule',
      'mymodule.c',
      dependencies: [eggdrop_core_dep],
      name_prefix: '',
      install: true,
      install_dir: eggdrop_moddir,
    )

   If your module requires external dependencies, add them to the
   dependencies list. Examine src/mod/*/meson.build for examples.

3. Create a MODULE.c file (where MODULE is your module name). This file
   must include the required defines and functions described below.

4. Update src/mod/meson.build to include your new module directory:

    subdir('mymodule.mod')

REQUIRED MODULE CODE

Your module MUST include:

1. Define your module name:

    #define MODULE_NAME "mymodule"

2. Define a guard macro for the module (all caps):

    #define MAKING_MYMODULE

3. Include the module header:

    #include "../module.h"

   This provides access to Eggdrop's global function table and module
   API. Consult src/mod/module.h for available functions.

4. Include standard C headers as needed. Note that stdio.h, string.h,
   stdlib.h, and sys/types.h are already included by module.h.

5. Declare a global function table pointer:

    Function *global;

   This variable provides access to all Eggdrop functions. Without it,
   your module cannot load.

MODULE STRUCTURE GUIDELINES

Good module practices:
- Make all functions and variables static (except global and MODULE_start)
  to minimize module size.
- Keep functions focused and under 50 lines when possible.
- Use the libop utility library (op_strbuf_t, op_cidr_tbl, etc.) for
  string and data structure manipulation.
- Validate all input at module boundaries.
- Handle errors explicitly and provide clear error messages.

MODULE ENTRY POINTS

Every module requires these four functions, exported in MODULE_table:

MODULE_start

    char *MODULE_start(Function *func_table)

Called when the module is first loaded. This function must:

    global = func_table;

  Assign the global function table to enable function calls.

    module_register(MODULE_NAME, MODULE_table, MAJOR, MINOR);

  Register the module with Eggdrop, where MAJOR and MINOR are version
  numbers. MODULE_table is your function export table (see below).

    module_depend(MODULE_NAME, "dependency-name", MAJOR, MINOR);

  If your module depends on another module, declare that dependency.
  Eggdrop will attempt to load dependencies automatically. Return 0 on
  success, non-zero to fail.

Return NULL on success. Return a non-NULL error string if the module
cannot load; any dependent modules will also fail to load.

MODULE_table

    static Function *MODULE_table[] = {
      MODULE_start,
      MODULE_close,
      MODULE_expmem,
      MODULE_report,
      ... other exported functions
    };

This table exports functions that other modules or Eggdrop can call.
The first four entries are REQUIRED and must be in this order:
  1. MODULE_start (char *(Function *))
  2. MODULE_close (char *())
  3. MODULE_expmem (int ())
  4. MODULE_report (void (int))

MODULE_close

    static char *MODULE_close(void)

Called when the module is unloaded. This function must:

    module_undepend(MODULE_NAME);

  Inform Eggdrop that this module no longer depends on anything.

Clean up any allocated resources (registered hooks, Tcl commands,
allocated memory, etc.).

Return NULL on success. Return a non-NULL error string if the module
cannot be unloaded. See mod.blowfish for an example.

MODULE_expmem

    static int MODULE_expmem(void)

Tally all memory allocated within the module (using nmalloc, nfree, etc.)
and return the total in bytes. This is used for memory debugging and the
.status command.

MODULE_report

    static void MODULE_report(int idx)

Provide a brief status report for the .module or .status commands. Use
dprintf to send output to the given DCC connection index.

AVAILABLE MODULE FUNCTIONS

The following functions are commonly used by modules. See src/mod/module.h
for the complete function table.

Memory Management

nmalloc(size)

  Allocate size bytes of memory. Returns a pointer to the allocated block.

nfree(ptr)

  Free an nmalloc'd block of memory.

Hooks

add_hook(hook_num, func)
del_hook(hook_num, func)

  Register or unregister a hook function. Valid hooks:

    HOOK_SECONDLY     — fired every second
    HOOK_MINUTELY     — fired every minute
    HOOK_5MINUTELY    — fired every 5 minutes
    HOOK_HOURLY       — fired hourly
    HOOK_DAILY        — fired when logfiles rotate
    HOOK_READ_USERFILE — when userfile is read
    HOOK_USERFILE     — when userfile is written
    HOOK_PRE_REHASH   — before rehash
    HOOK_REHASH       — after rehash
    HOOK_IDLE         — when DCC idle for 1 second
    HOOK_BACKUP       — on backup
    HOOK_LOADED       — on initial load
    HOOK_DIE          — before shutdown

Module Management

module_rename(old_name, new_name)

  Rename a loaded module.

module_find(name, major, minor)

  Search for a loaded module by name and version. Returns a module_entry
  structure with name, major, minor, and funcs fields.

module_load(name)
module_unload(name)

  Dynamically load or unload a module by name. Returns NULL on success,
  or an error message on failure.

Tcl Integration

add_tcl_commands(table)
rem_tcl_commands(table)

  Register or unregister a table of Tcl commands. Table format:

    static tcl_cmds my_cmds[] = {
      {"mycommand", my_cmd_func},
      {NULL, NULL}
    };

add_tcl_ints(table)
rem_tcl_ints(table)

  Register or unregister links between C int variables and Tcl variables.
  Table format:

    static tcl_ints my_ints[] = {
      {"myint", &my_c_variable, 0},
      {NULL, NULL, 0}
    };

  The last parameter is readonly flag (0 = writable, 1 = read-only).

add_tcl_strings(table)
rem_tcl_strings(table)

  Register or unregister links between C strings and Tcl variables.
  Table format:

    static tcl_strings my_strs[] = {
      {"mystr", my_string, sizeof(my_string), 0},
      {NULL, NULL, 0, 0}
    };

  Flags: 0 for normal, STR_DIR appends '/', STR_PROTECT marks as protected.

Tcl Binds

add_builtins(table, cmds)
rem_builtins(table, cmds)

  Register or unregister Tcl bind handlers. Works exactly like Tcl's bind
  command. Table format:

    static cmd_t my_binds[] = {
      {"command", "flags", my_handler, "displayname"},
      {NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL}
    };

Logging and Output

dprintf(idx, fmt, ...)

  Output to DCC connection idx, or use special destinations:

    DP_LOG     — log file
    DP_STDOUT  — standard output
    DP_MODE    — mode queue to server
    DP_SERVER  — normal queue to server
    DP_HELP    — help queue to server

putlog(mode, channel, fmt, ...)

  Log text to appropriate logfile. Output goes to user consoles with the
  matching console mode enabled.

MODULE BUILD INTEGRATION

The Meson build system automatically discovers and builds modules in
src/mod/*/. Modules are built as position-independent shared objects
with full compiler hardening (PIE, LTO, stack protection).

If your module has special build requirements (external dependencies,
custom compiler flags), add them to your meson.build file:

    eggdrop_mod_mymodule = shared_library('mymodule',
      'mymodule.c',
      c_args: ['-DSPECIAL_FLAG'],
      dependencies: [eggdrop_core_dep, dependency('libz')],
      name_prefix: '',
      install: true,
      install_dir: eggdrop_moddir,
    )

DISTRIBUTION

To share your module with the Eggdrop community:

1. Create a descriptive MODULE.desc file explaining your module's
   functionality and compatibility.

2. Include clear documentation of all configuration options and commands.

3. Specify the Eggdrop version your module was written for.

4. Test on multiple platforms if possible.

5. Share in #eggdrop on Libera Chat or via GitHub.

For more examples, examine the source code of modules in src/mod/ and
consult src/mod/module.h for the complete API.

